  <body>
    <main class="page">
      <header class="hero">
        <a class="home-link" href="/" aria-label="Back to home">sokolsky.me</a>
        <p class="eyebrow">Book notes · Eric Berne, 1964</p>
        <h1>Games People Play</h1>
        <p class="dek">
          Eric Berne gave names to arguments that seem spontaneous but somehow
          always end in the same place.
        </p>
      </header>

      <article class="article">
        <section id="bottom-line" aria-labelledby="bottom-line-heading">
          <h2 id="bottom-line-heading">Bottom line</h2>
          <p>
            Berne thinks a lot of social friction follows a script. One person says
            something plausible, a second message passes underneath and both
            people help steer the exchange toward a familiar ending. He calls the
            whole sequence a <em>game</em>. The payoff is often a bad feeling that
            confirms an old belief: “Nobody helps me,” “I always get blamed,”
            “People cannot be trusted” or “I was right to be angry.”
          </p>
          <p>
            I found the names less useful than the sequences. Once an argument
            starts to feel weirdly rehearsed, it helps to look past its stated
            subject and trace what each person did to keep it going. Berne is much
            less convincing when he jumps from a memorable patient story to a
            general claim about why people behave as they do.
          </p>
          <blockquote>
            <p>
              <em>The book is good at spotting loops. It is a poor excuse for
              diagnosing whoever annoyed you this week.</em>
            </p>
          </blockquote>
        </section>

        <section id="model" aria-labelledby="model-heading">
          <h2 id="model-heading">The model in five minutes</h2>
          <p>
            Berne begins with three <em>ego states</em>: coherent ways of feeling,
            thinking and behaving that can become active in any person. They are
            not ages, moral rankings or fixed personality types.
          </p>
          <div class="ego-states" aria-label="The three ego states">
            <div class="ego-state">
              <p class="state-letter" aria-hidden="true">P</p>
              <h3>Parent</h3>
              <p>
                Borrowed rules, judgments and caretaking patterns learned from
                authority figures. It can protect and guide—or criticize and
                control.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="ego-state">
              <p class="state-letter" aria-hidden="true">A</p>
              <h3>Adult</h3>
              <p>
                Present-focused reality testing: gathering information, weighing
                options and responding to what is happening now.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="ego-state">
              <p class="state-letter" aria-hidden="true">C</p>
              <h3>Child</h3>
              <p>
                Earlier feelings, impulses and adaptations. It contains fear and
                rebellion, but also play, affection, curiosity and creativity.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p>
            A <em>transaction</em> is one unit of social exchange: a stimulus and a
            response. “Where are the keys?” followed by “On the desk” is a direct
            Adult-to-Adult transaction. “Where are the keys?” followed by “You
            always blame me” crosses the lines: an Adult question receives a Child
            response aimed at a Parent. Now the keys have to wait. The two people
            are arguing about blame.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="social-time" aria-labelledby="social-time-heading">
          <h2 id="social-time-heading">How people structure time</h2>
          <p>
            Games are one of six ways Berne says people fill time together. He
            orders them by how much personal exposure they allow:
          </p>
          <ol class="ladder">
            <li>
              <strong>Withdrawal</strong>
              <span>Staying physically or psychologically apart.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Rituals</strong>
              <span>Predictable exchanges such as greetings and courtesies.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Pastimes</strong>
              <span>Safe, semi-scripted talk used to fill time and test compatibility.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Activities</strong>
              <span>Working together on an explicit task in external reality.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Games</strong>
              <span>Repetitive exchanges with a concealed level and a payoff.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Intimacy</strong>
              <span>Direct, candid contact without a concealed bargain.</span>
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            Each form provides <em>strokes</em>, Berne’s term for units of
            recognition. A compliment is a stroke. So is an insult. People
            sometimes settle for the insult because they know how to obtain it;
            asking openly for affection is riskier.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="anatomy" aria-labelledby="anatomy-heading">
          <h2 id="anatomy-heading">Anatomy of a game</h2>
          <p>
            Berne defines a game as “an ongoing series of complementary ulterior
            transactions progressing to a well-defined, predictable outcome”
            (<a href="https://ericberne.com/games-people-play/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">quoted here by the Eric Berne family site</a>).
            The conversation has a trapdoor. At some familiar cue, the stated
            subject drops away and the real quarrel begins.
          </p>
          <div class="sequence" aria-label="Sequence of a psychological game">
            <div>
              <span>1</span>
              <p><strong>Hook</strong><br />An invitation that looks straightforward.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <span>2</span>
              <p><strong>Hidden bargain</strong><br />Both parties answer a second, unspoken message.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <span>3</span>
              <p><strong>Switch</strong><br />The apparent situation changes abruptly.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <span>4</span>
              <p><strong>Payoff</strong><br />Everyone lands in a familiar role or feeling.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p>
            Games survive because every player gets something from them, even when
            the result is unpleasant. One game provides an excuse to stay angry.
            Another gets sympathy without requiring a direct request. A third
            keeps two people talking while making sure neither has to say anything
            vulnerable.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="games" aria-labelledby="games-heading">
          <h2 id="games-heading">The most useful games to recognize</h2>
          <div class="game-list">
            <article>
              <h3>Why Don’t You—Yes But</h3>
              <p>
                Someone presents a problem. Others offer solutions; each gets a
                “Yes, but…” The stated goal is advice, but the payoff is proving
                that the problem is uniquely unsolvable and that nobody can help.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Exit:</strong> ask whether the person wants ideas, empathy or simply to be heard.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>If It Weren’t for You</h3>
              <p>
                A person blames a partner or circumstance for limiting them. The
                restriction also protects them from discovering their own fear or
                reluctance. When the obstacle disappears, another often takes its
                place.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Exit:</strong> separate the real constraint from the choice it helps you avoid.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Now I’ve Got You</h3>
              <p>
                A small error becomes permission for disproportionate outrage.
                The mistake is not the real prize; the long-awaited right to
                prosecute is.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Exit:</strong> address the concrete error at its actual scale.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>See What You Made Me Do</h3>
              <p>
                Someone responds badly to an interruption or request, then makes
                the other person responsible for the response. The payoff is
                exporting responsibility while preserving righteous anger.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Exit:</strong> own your action before discussing the other person’s contribution.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Kick Me</h3>
              <p>
                A person repeatedly behaves in ways likely to provoke rejection or
                punishment, then treats the result as proof that others are cruel
                or that they are doomed.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Exit:</strong> examine the move just before the predictable rejection.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>I’m Only Trying to Help You</h3>
              <p>
                A helper keeps offering interventions that fail, while the
                recipient remains helpless. Both can preserve a preferred
                identity: indispensable rescuer and incurable case.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Exit:</strong> agree on ownership, consent and what a successful result would be.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Blemish</h3>
              <p>
                A person searches for a small flaw in someone otherwise admirable.
                Finding it restores emotional distance and protects against envy,
                admiration or intimacy.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Exit:</strong> notice when accurate criticism is being used to dismiss the whole person.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Wooden Leg</h3>
              <p>
                A limitation becomes a blanket exemption: “What do you expect from
                someone with my background, diagnosis or circumstances?” A real
                constraint is stretched until it rules out all agency.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Exit:</strong> ask what remains possible without denying the limitation.</p>
            </article>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section id="degrees" aria-labelledby="degrees-heading">
          <h2 id="degrees-heading">Not every game is equally serious</h2>
          <p>
            Berne distinguishes games by intensity. A first-degree game is mostly
            socially acceptable and may end in irritation or gossip. A
            second-degree game is kept out of public view because the damage is
            more humiliating or consequential. A third-degree game ends at the
            level of the courtroom, hospital or morgue.
          </p>
          <p>
            Calling all three “patterns” can blur differences in harm. An awkward
            recurring conversation does not belong in the same category as abuse,
            addiction or violence.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="using-it" aria-labelledby="using-it-heading">
          <h2 id="using-it-heading">How to use the book without becoming unbearable</h2>
          <ul class="questions">
            <li>
              <strong>Start with your own payoff.</strong> Naming somebody else’s
              “game” is often just a sophisticated move in a new game.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Describe the sequence, not the person.</strong> “We reject
              every proposed solution” is more useful than “You’re playing Why
              Don’t You—Yes But.”
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Check the social and psychological levels.</strong> What is
              being said openly? What response is being invited underneath?
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Look for the switch.</strong> At what moment does a normal
              exchange turn into confusion, accusation or helplessness?
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Return to Adult.</strong> State the observable issue, ask a
              direct question and make responsibility explicit.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Offer a non-game alternative.</strong> A pattern weakens
              when the underlying need can be expressed without the trap.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="dated" aria-labelledby="dated-heading">
          <h2 id="dated-heading">What has not aged well</h2>
          <p>
            A lot of the book reads like 1964 because it is. The gender roles are
            rigid. The chapters on sexuality contain language and assumptions that
            now sound ugly. Berne also generalizes freely from the patients he saw.
            His chapter on “Alcoholic” treats drinking mainly as part of a social
            game; that account cannot replace current medical knowledge about
            substance-use disorders.
          </p>
          <p>
            The recurring sequence, hidden message and payoff are things a reader
            can watch for. Berne’s explanations of what caused them are often
            guesses. The labels become silly fast when treated as final answers.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="beyond" aria-labelledby="beyond-heading">
          <h2 id="beyond-heading">Beyond games</h2>
          <p>
            Berne calls the alternative <em>autonomy</em>. He breaks it into three
            capacities:
          </p>
          <dl class="autonomy">
            <div>
              <dt>Awareness</dt>
              <dd>Perceiving the present directly rather than only through inherited categories.</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Spontaneity</dt>
              <dd>Having a real choice among responses instead of replaying the assigned one.</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Intimacy</dt>
              <dd>Candid, game-free contact in which neither person needs a concealed payoff.</dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
          <p>
            Parent and Child remain part of the person. Autonomy means having some
            choice about who answers. Care, play, judgment and reason can then
            appear when the moment calls for them instead of arriving on cue from
            an old script.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="sources" aria-labelledby="sources-heading">
          <h2 id="sources-heading">Sources and edition note</h2>
          <p>
            This summary is based primarily on the supplied 2011 Tantor eBook,
            <cite>Games People Play: The Basic Handbook of Transactional Analysis</cite>,
            including James R. Allen’s introduction and Kurt Vonnegut’s 1965
            commentary. Publication context and terminology were cross-checked
            against the <a href="https://ericberne.com/games-people-play/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Eric Berne family site’s book guide</a>
            and its <a href="https://ericberne.com/transactional-analysis/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">introduction to transactional analysis</a>.
            The book was first published by Grove Press in 1964.
          </p>
        </section>
      </article>
    </main>
  </body>
</html>

<style>
